WordPress.com, unlike WordPress.org (self-hosted WordPress), has certain restrictions on adding custom JavaScript directly to posts for security reasons. However, you can add JavaScript to a WordPress.com site using widgets, plugins, or through the Customizer (if you have the appropriate plan that enables you to add custom code).

If you have a WordPress.com Business plan or higher, you have the option to include custom JavaScript directly on your site. Below is a simple JavaScript function example and how you could theoretically add it to a widget if your plan allows for custom code:

First, here's a simple JavaScript function:

```javascript
// A function to display a greeting
function displayGreeting() {
    alert("Hello, welcome to my WordPress post!");
}
```

To add this to a WordPress.com site through a widget, you can follow these steps:

1. From your WordPress.com dashboard, go to Appearance > Customize, which will take you to the Theme Customizer.
2. Navigate to the Widgets section.
3. Select the area where you want to add the custom JavaScript - usually, the footer or sidebar is allowed.
4. Click on "Add a Widget" and search for the Custom HTML widget.
5. Add the Custom HTML widget to your selected area.
6. In the Custom HTML widget, add a script tag with your JavaScript code:

```html
<script type="text/javascript">
// A function to display a greeting
function displayGreeting() {
   alert("Hello, welcome to my WordPress post!");
}

// Call the function when the window loads
window.onload = function() {
   displayGreeting();
};
</script>
```

7. Click "Publish" to save your changes.

Remember, if you don't have a business plan or higher, you won't be able to add JavaScript directly. A workaround for this limitation is to use embeddable widgets or services that provide the functionality you need and allow you to embed their code into your WordPress.com site.

Also, if you are embedding code, always ensure that it's from a trusted source to avoid security risks. Untrusted code can potentially harm your website and compromise user data.

To post on WordPress.com using the REST API, you first need to authenticate and obtain an access token, which requires a multi-step OAuth 2.0 process. Please take note that your "Client Secret" is sensitive information and should not be exposed on the client side (such as JavaScript running in the browser). The steps described here should be performed on the server-side for security reasons.

However, I’ll assume that we’re dealing with a simplified scenario and provide you with an understanding of how you would theoretically interact with the WordPress REST API using JavaScript. In a real-world application, you would have a backend server handling the sensitive parts of the OAuth process.

**Step 1: Authentication (assuming this process has been done elsewhere securely to get an access token)**

Once you have obtained an access token securely via the backend (which should use the client secret), you would typically send it to the client application. NEVER expose your client secret on the frontend.

**Step 2: Making an API call to create a post**

Here’s a general outline of how you would use JavaScript to create a new post using the WordPress REST API when you already have an access token:

```javascript
// Function to create a new post on WordPress
function createWordPressPost(accessToken, title, content) {
    const postUrl = 'https://public-api.wordpress.com/rest/v1.1/sites/your-site-id/posts/new';

    // The data we are going to send in our request
    let data = {
        title: title,
        content: content,
        // Additional fields like status can be included as well
        // status: 'publish', // or 'draft' based on need
    };

    // Create request
    let xhr = new XMLHttpRequest();
    xhr.open('POST', postUrl, true);
    xhr.setRequestHeader('Authorization', 'Bearer ' + accessToken);
    xhr.setRequestHeader('Content-Type', 'application/json');

    xhr.onreadystatechange = function () {
        if (xhr.readyState === 4 && xhr.status === 201) {
            console.log('Post created successfully:');
            console.log(JSON.parse(xhr.responseText));
        } else if (xhr.readyState === 4) {
            console.error('Error creating post:');
            console.error(xhr.responseText);
        }
    };

    // Send request
    xhr.send(JSON.stringify(data));
}

// Usage example (use real access token and proper data)
createWordPressPost('your-real-access-token', 'Post Title', 'Post content goes here.');
```

This is a basic example, but remember:

1. "your-real-access-token" should be an actual authenticated token retrieved from authentication step.
2. "your-site-id" should be your site's specific identifier or domain on WordPress.com API path.

Please be cautious with handling authentication tokens. This process should ideally be implemented on a server to keep your client secret secure. Always validate the token on the server prior to making API calls on behalf of the client, and ensure your application follows best practices in terms of security to protect user data.

If you're operating under WordPress.com's limitations that prevent server-side code execution, you may need to look into WordPress plugins that handle interactions with the WordPress REST API, or consider migrating to a self-hosted WordPress.org setup for more control and custom server-side code execution.

As previously mentioned, handling OAuth authentication securely should really be done server-side rather than client-side. Exposing your client secret or access tokens in client-side code poses a significant security risk. 

However, for educational purposes only, I’ll demonstrate how you could theoretically call the WordPress REST API to create a post using JavaScript in the browser, assuming you have already obtained an access token securely and it is available to your client-side script without exposing any sensitive information.

Here is a simple client-side JavaScript function that uses the `fetch` API to send a POST request to the WordPress REST API:

```javascript
// Function to create a new post on WordPress
function createWordPressPost(accessToken, siteId, title, content) {
    const postUrl = `https://public-api.wordpress.com/rest/v1.2/sites/${siteId}/posts/new`;

    // The data we are going to send in our request
    let data = {
        title: title,
        content: content,
        // You can add other post attributes such as 'status', 'categories', 'tags', etc.
    };

    // Use the Fetch API to make the network request
    fetch(postUrl, {
        method: 'POST',
        headers: new Headers({
            'Authorization': 'Bearer ' + accessToken,
            'Content-Type': 'application/json'
        }),
        body: JSON.stringify(data)
    })
    .then(response => {
        if (!response.ok) {
            throw new Error('Network response was not ok: ' + response.statusText);
        }
        return response.json();
    })
    .then(data => {
        console.log('Post created successfully:', data);
    })
    .catch(error => {
        console.error('Error creating post:', error);
    });
}

// Example usage (replace with actual access token and site ID)
createWordPressPost('your-real-access-token', 'your-site-id-or-domain', 'Sample Post Title', '<p>This is the post content.</p>');
```

Please replace `'your-real-access-token'` with the actual access token obtained through secure means, and `'your-site-id-or-domain'` with the site ID or domain for your WordPress.com site.

In a real-world application, you would need to:

1. Implement a secure OAuth flow to obtain the access token, typically involving server-side code to keep the client secret secure.
2. Securely transmit the access token to the client-side code without exposing it.
3. Implement appropriate error handling and user feedback mechanisms.
4. Ensure to follow the WordPress.com API rate limits and terms of use to avoid being blocked or banned from their services.

Keep in mind, if you are using WordPress.com to host your website and you are not on a plan that allows for custom plugins, you might be limited in your ability to include custom JavaScript. Always verify what is permissible within your specific WordPress.com hosting plan.

For security reasons, it's critical to note that you should never use your client secret directly in a Chrome extension or any client-side code that users can access. The client secret should remain confidential and only be used in server-to-server communications. Including it in a Chrome extension could lead to unauthorized access to your WordPress account.

Since you are using a Chrome Extension, it's essential to conduct the initial OAuth flow outside of the extension (e.g., on a server you control) to securely get the `access_token`. Afterwards, you can manage token storage and refresh using appropriate and secure methods.

To illustrate the process, let's presume you already have an `access_token` that was securely obtained and stored in the extension's context or passed to it. Here's how a function in a Chrome Extension could look like to create a WordPress.com post:

```javascript
// This function assumes you already have a valid access_token
function createWordPressPost(siteId, title, content) {
    const postUrl = `https://public-api.wordpress.com/rest/v1.2/sites/${siteId}/posts/new`;

    // Post data
    const data = {
        title: title,
        content: content,
        // Additional post attributes like 'status', 'categories', 'tags', etc. can be added
    };

    // Retrieve the access token from storage - replace with your extension's storage retrieval method
    chrome.storage.local.get('access_token', function(items) {
        const accessToken = items.access_token; // replace appropriately based on actual storage key

        if (accessToken) {
            // Execute the API call to create a new post
            fetch(postUrl, {
                method: 'POST',
                headers: {
                    'Authorization': 'Bearer ' + accessToken,
                    'Content-Type': 'application/json'
                },
                body: JSON.stringify(data)
            })
            .then(response => response.json())
            .then(post => console.log('Post created:', post))
            .catch(error => console.error('Error creating post:', error));
        } else {
            console.error('Access token is not available.');
        }
    });
}

// Usage (replace 'your-site-id' with actual site ID and insert real post title and content)
createWordPressPost('your-site-id', 'My New Post Title', '<p>This is my new post content.</p>');
```

Please replace `'your-site-id'` with your actual WordPress site ID, and provide real title and content for the new post.

