Certainly! Bookmarklets are tiny pieces of JavaScript code that can be saved as bookmarks and run on any page in the browser. If you want to convert the bookmarklet into a regular JavaScript function, the code needs to be slightly adjusted to fit a typical function structure.

The JavaScript function would take an argument that is the URL you want to post to WordPress.com. It opens a new window or tab with the WordPress.com post editor and pre-populates the URL, title, and any selected text from the current page.

The converted function would look like this:

```javascript
function postToWordPress() {
    // Base URL for WordPress new post page
    const wordpressBaseURL = 'https://wordpress.com/post/paidpursuit.wordpress.com';

    // Get details from the current document
    let doc = document;
    let win = window;
    let curURL = encodeURIComponent(doc.location.href);
    let curTitle = encodeURIComponent(doc.title);
    let curSelection = '';

    // Get selected text if any
    if (window.getSelection) {
        curSelection = encodeURIComponent(win.getSelection().toString());
    } else if (doc.getSelection) {
        curSelection = encodeURIComponent(doc.getSelection().toString());
    } else if (doc.selection) {
        curSelection = encodeURIComponent(doc.selection.createRange().text);
    }

    // Construct the WordPress new post URL
    let wordpressPostURL = `${wordpressBaseURL}?url=${curURL}&title=${curTitle}&text=${curSelection}&v=5`;

    // Open the WordPress new post page
    let popup = win.open(wordpressPostURL, 't', 'toolbar=0,resizable=1,scrollbars=1,status=1,width=660,height=570');

    // Fallback if popup is blocked
    if (!popup) {
        document.location.href = wordpressPostURL;
    }
}

// Call the function to execute
postToWordPress();
```

This function can now be called from anywhere within your JavaScript code to perform the action that was previously done via the bookmarklet. Remember that popup blockers in web browsers might prevent the `window.open` from successfully opening a new window, so that is why there is a fallback that sends the user to the desired WordPress URL if the popup fails.
